Each set is defined by its starting number \( N \), which can be expressed as \( N = 10(k-1) + 1 \) for \( k \) ranging from 1 to 100. We need to find the values of \( k \) such that the set starting at \( N \) contains exactly two multiples of 7. A number \( N \) will have two multiples of 7 in the set \( \{N, N+1, \ldots, N+9\} \) if and only if \( N \equiv 0, 3, \) or \( 5 \pmod{7} \). This is derived from
